'''Obaka Kofun''' (小墓古墳) is a {{ill|Kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft}} Kofun located in {{ill|Tenri City|ja|天理市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|12=draft}}, Japan. It is a keyhole-shaped Kofun (前方後円墳) and one of the mounds comprising the {{ill|Somanouchi Kofun Group|ja|杣之内古墳群|1=Somanouchi Kofun cluster|12=draft}}. The site has not been Historic Site1 as a historic landmark.  

== Overview ==  
Obaka Kofun was constructed at the western end of a ridge running east-west along the eastern edge of the {{ill|Nara Basin|ja|奈良盆地|12=draft}}. Together with the {{ill|Nishinorikura Kofun|ja|西乗鞍古墳|12=draft}} and {{ill|Higashinorikura Kofun|ja|東乗鞍古墳|12=draft}}, it types part of a subgroup within the Somanouchi Kofun Group. The northern side of the rear circular portion has been flattened, and excavations were conducted on the eastern side of the mound in 1987 and 1989.  

The mound is keyhole-shaped, with the rectangular portion oriented to the southwest. It features a three-tier construction. A moat encircles the mound in a shield-like type, measuring 12–13 meters in width.{{Sfn|Obaka Kofun (Zoku Nihon Kofun Daijiten)|2002}} burial goods recovered from the moat include cylindrical {{ill|haniwa|ja|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa|12=draft}} (including morning-glory-shaped haniwa) and shaped haniwa, such as lid-shaped, shield-shaped, quiver-shaped, human-shaped, horse-shaped, deer-shaped, waterfowl-shaped, rooster-shaped, and house-shaped haniwa. Wooden burial goods resembling haniwa, such as lid-shaped, shield-shaped, sword-shaped, scepter-shaped, and halberd-shaped items, have also been discovered. Among these, elevated-floor building models with cylindrical columns are particularly notable. Other finds include wooden troughs, mallets, fire-starting implements, ear-cup-shaped containers, and wooden poles and stakes. The burial chamber has not been identified.  

The construction period is estimated to be the early 6th century, during the early {{ill|late Kofun period|ja|古墳時代後期|12=draft}}. Nishinorikura Kofun and Higashinorikura Kofun, located nearby and dating to the late mid-Kofun to early late-Kofun periods, are also hypothesized to be the Kofuns of {{ill|Mononobe clan|ja|物部氏|12=draft}} chiefs.<ref>{{Cite book|和書|author=Shiraishi Taichirō|chapter=The Mononobe Clan Viewed from Kofun|title=Reasoning About the Buried of Kofun (Chūkō Series)|publisher=[[Chūōkōron-shinsha]]|year=2018|pages=253-260}}</ref>  

== Mound burial ==  
The area of the mound are as follows:{{Sfn|Obaka Kofun (Zoku Nihon Kofun Daijiten)|2002}}  
* Mound length: 80.5 meters (estimated restoration: over 85 meters)  
* Rear circular portion: Three-tier construction  
** Height: 7.8 meters  
* Front rectangular portion: Three-tier construction  
** Width: 46 meters  
** Height: 6.1 meters  

<gallery>  
File:小墓古墳出土 家形埴輪.JPG|House-shaped haniwa<br/>{{small|Photographed during a special exhibit at the Nara Prefecture Kashihara Archaeological Institute Museum.}}  
File:小墓古墳出土 埴輪 盾持人.JPG|Shield-bearer haniwa<br/>{{small|Photographed during a special exhibit at the Karako Kagi Archaeological Museum.}}  
File:小墓古墳出土 埴輪 人物（男性）・甲冑・猪.JPG|Human figure (male) with armor and boar haniwa<br/>{{small|Photographed during a special exhibit at the Karako Kagi Archaeological Museum.}}  
</gallery>  

